{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"alias":"unsalty-flattish-bagworm","creation_channel":"cli","description":"## Context\nrebar records a rich, durable, event-sourced history — ticket events on the `tickets` branch (compaction renames folded events to committed `.retired` files, so the raw history survives synced), gate sidecars (`REVIEW_RESULT`, `COMPLETION_VERDICT`), the two-file module-size ratchet, and git — but there is no aggregation layer and no way to ask \"how is the agent-driven dev loop trending over time?\". Several agent-lifecycle signals are blindspots today (env/integration-diagnosis time, \"which change caused a bug\", replanning/escalation classification), and code-health movement (coverage/complexity/clone) is computed ephemerally in CI and never persisted. This epic delivers a single dynamic date-range `rebar metrics` command surfacing every available metric across three lenses — is the agent loop working, is the codebase decaying, are the gates worth it — plus the minimal passive instrumentation to close the blindspots without any new agent-facing manual command.\n\n## Success Criteria\n- `rebar metrics --since <date> --until <date>` emits a machine-readable artifact spanning agent-process, gate-economics, and code-health metrics, with real date-range trends for every metric that has a complete history.\n- The command is built once against a complete metric registry: metrics whose signals have not yet accrued report a structured `unavailable` state and light up automatically as data arrives, with no future code change.\n- Tier-C blindspots are captured passively: env/integration-diagnosis via an `ERROR` outcome on the existing gate sidecars; bug provenance via a new `caused_by` link relation (auto-derived from blame, plus an optional param); bug classification via a persisted close `--class` enum replacing today's validated-then-discarded free-text reason.\n- Net process friction does not increase.\n- Historical data is backfilled wherever a durable source exists; backfilled/classified values are labeled with `source`+`confidence` and segregated from authoritative structural signals.\n\n## Approach\nDerive-structurally over the durable event store (including `.retired` events) for everything with a clean event signature; add the smallest possible passive emission only where a signal genuinely leaves no trace, always stamped by trustworthy code (gate error handlers, git blame) rather than agent self-report — the layered-hybrid design that dev-analytics (DevLake, Swarmia) and agent-observability practice converge on, and that fits rebar's event-sourced substrate. We reuse existing surfaces (gate sidecars, the `transition` command, the link-relation set) rather than introduce a new event type, keeping every change additive and back-compatible (old records stay valid; readers tolerate absence). The command and its structural sources are harness- and target-project-agnostic (a rebar CLI over the portable event store); harness/CI-specific backfills are isolated optional adapters the core command never depends on.\n\n## Decomposition\nThree tracks; each child is a single concern (detail lives in the children):\n- Command: metric-registry + unavailable/label contract; event-derivation readers; git-derivation readers; gate-sidecar reader + `ERROR` path; going-forward snapshot writer/reader; the `rebar metrics` CLI.\n- Instrumentation: the `caused_by` link relation (additive); the bug close `--class` enum (persisted, replacing the discarded reason); blame-based `caused_by` auto-derivation + `--caused-by` param + bug-template advisory.\n- Backfill (one-time, labeled): `caused_by` over existing bugs; historical bug `--class` from structural signals; complexity/clone snapshots at sampled commits; local Claude-Code-transcript mining (optional adapter); GitHub-Actions coverage + CI-health harvest (optional adapter).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] All child tickets are closed (epic rollup), verified by `rebar list --epic <this> --status open` returning none.\n- [ ] `rebar metrics --since 2026-01-01 --until 2026-07-01 --output json` exits 0 and emits JSON where every registered metric key is present with either a value or `{\"unavailable\":{\"reason\",\"accruing_since\"}}` — an integration test asserts via `jq -e` that no registered metric key is absent.\n- [ ] Every metric entry carries `source` and `confidence`, and a `source=backfill_classified` value is never aggregated into an authoritative structural series — a unit test asserts the segregation.\n- [ ] Bug-close friction does not increase: the required free-text reason is replaced by a bounded `--class` enum persisted on the STATUS event, verified by `rebar show <closed-bug> --output json | jq -e '.close_class'`.","id":"86ac-086a-20ad-4327","parent_id":"","priority":2,"tags":["metrics","observability","agent-lifecycle"],"ticket_type":"epic","title":"Passive metrics + agent-lifecycle instrumentation (rebar metrics command)"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1784416380420331001,"uuid":"d4d894c7-3005-4bb0-ae1e-13d6c668f2e1"}